Title: Us
Comment: This was such a tough week. When every song in recorded history is available, well those on Spotify anyway, how can you choose? How do I want to introduce myself? What aspect of my personality do I want to express? In the end I chose this as it is one of the most important songs in my life, to me it is beautiful, dramatic and euphoric. I love to sing along, even though I don't have the necessary control and it is nowhere near my range. And, I hope you will forgive a moment of soppy-ness, it always makes me think about how much I love my other half.

Title: Man in the Mirror - 2012 Remaster
Comment:
Roundhay Park, Leeds, 16th August 1992.

Understandably I think I'm going to get downvoted for this because Michael Jackson was a nonce.  It was the first concert I went to though and to be fair I didn't know he was a nonce in '92.  It was meant to be my Mum and Dad going but my Mum couldn't make it so I was drafted in to go with my Dad.

Picked this song because he ended the set with it and it was my favourite song of Jackson's when I was little and still listened to him.

I won‚Äôt name the venue as it might give me away. Ps I still have the ticket stub if the fun police want to verify this is legit.

Title: Rock & Roll Queen
Comment:
8th April 2006, Liverpool Carling Academy. I went to see The Subways with Tom Muise and Dave Fellows and his girlfriend. We were 14. I bought a tshirt. Muisey managed to get us some horrible pints of Carling. David Fellows kept necking his lass. An older man, a kind of Ian Brown x Ricky Tomlinson hybrid in a white adidas tracksuit and aviator sunglasses, offered us a gary each in the toilets. We refused. 

Afterwards, we went to Paddy's Bar on London Road and got served. Went there almost every Friday night until we turned 18. The old Irish ladies behind the bar, Anne and Frances (both easily in their 70s) were like grandmothers to us and I'll never forget them. 

The Subways? Forgot all about them until this week.

(Sidenote: Paddy's had one of the greatest bits of toilet grafitti responses I've ever seen: "If Ireland's so great, what the fuck are you all doing here?" "Shitting".)

Goul el hak el mout kaina
Album: Goul el hak el mout kaina
Comment:
Samples are one of my favourite things, so this is one of my favourite rounds. 

And this sample is brilliant. The thought of the Chemical Brothers hearing this slice of Moroccan Chaabi music from 1987 on a trip to Tangier and turning it into Galvanize is absolutely thrilling. Especially when you get Q-Tip, a sampling monster, on vocals too. The vision is exquisite. Chef's kiss.
